orth Yorkshire), most of which are named with the Old English personal name <i>Mūl(a)</i>, the Old Norse personal name <i>Múli</i>, or Old English <i>mūl</i> ‘mule’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."],"variants":[{"name":"Molden","meanings":["English:","metronymic from the Middle English female personal name <i>Mold</i>, a form of <i>Maud</i>, with the characteristically West Midland genitival suffix <i>-en</i>.","variant of   Moulton  ."]},{"name":"Moulden","meanings":["English: variant of   Moulton  ."]},{"name":"Molton","meanings":["English: variant of   Moulton  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":6,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":31,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":44,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":53,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Moulton was born about 1284, in Up Holland, Lancashire, England, his father, Sir Hubert de Moulton, was 32 and his mother, Ada de Brune, was 32. He married Joan de Latham in 1312, in England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 2 daughters. He died on 1 June 1365, in Bostock, Cheshire, England, at the age of 82."},"et":{"about 1284–1 June 1365":"umbes 1284–1. juuni 1365","1284–1365":"1284–1365","1286–Female":"1286–Surnud","1312–1383":"1312–1383","1319–Male":"1319–Surnud","1326–Female":"1326–Surnud","1339–1396":"1339–1396","1254–1300":"1254–1300","1254–Female":"1254–Surnud","1396":"1396","1286":"1286","before 10 July 1300":"enne 10. juulit 1300","1383":"1383","1284":"1284","1290":"1290","1326":"1326","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1312":"1312","1300":"1300","1 June 1365":"1. juuni 1365","1453":"1453","1365":"1365","1254":"1254","1319":"1319","about 1284":"umbes 1284","1339":"1339","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Up Holland, Lancashire, England":"Up Holland, Lancashire, England","England":"England","Moulton, Cheshire, England":"Moulton, Cheshire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Cumberland, England":"Cumberland, England","Bostock, Cheshire, England":"Bostock, Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1284–1 June 1365":"noin 1284–1. kesäkuuta 1365","1284–1365":"1284–1365","1286–Female":"1286–Kuollut","1312–1383":"1312–1383","1319–Male